{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569513"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22262"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22262"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.86,0.09,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15227"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15227"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"1409"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"},{"type":"tags","id":"6620"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40212"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-minute episode of sudden vision loss in his right eye and left-sided arm weakness that resolved spontaneously. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. He is a current smoker with a 20 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 78/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination is normal. A right carotid bruit is audible on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-contrast CT brain is performed and shows no acute abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to confirm the underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fundoscopy","Carotid duplex ultrasound","MRI brain with diffusion-weighted imaging","Transthoracic echocardiogram","Electrocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a transient ischaemic attack (TIA) with ipsilateral transient monocular vision loss (amaurosis fugax) and contralateral arm weakness. The presence of a right carotid bruit combined with these symptoms strongly suggests carotid atherosclerotic disease as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid duplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the underlying cause. It is non-invasive, widely available, and can accurately assess the degree of carotid stenosis. Given the carotid bruit and classic symptoms of carotid territory TIA, this investigation has the highest yield for identifying symptomatic carotid stenosis. Stenosis \u003E70% would require urgent vascular surgical review for consideration of carotid endarterectomy or stenting within two weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain with diffusion-weighted imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is more sensitive than CT for detecting small infarcts and can help confirm the diagnosis of TIA. However, it is less likely to identify the underlying cause compared to carotid imaging, particularly when there is already strong clinical evidence of carotid disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E could identify retinal pathology, but the brief duration of symptoms (two minutes) with complete resolution and concurrent contralateral motor symptoms make a retinal cause unlikely. Retinal conditions typically cause isolated visual symptoms without motor deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for investigating cardioembolic sources such as atrial thrombus or valvular vegetations. However, the presence of a carotid bruit and the pattern of symptoms (ipsilateral eye and contralateral arm) strongly point to carotid disease rather than cardioembolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed to detect atrial fibrillation, which is found in approximately 20% of TIA patients. While important in the overall workup, it is less likely to reveal the cause in this patient with clear evidence of carotid disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing confirmation of significant carotid stenosis, this patient would require urgent antiplatelet therapy, optimisation of vascular risk factors, and expedited vascular surgical review.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Carotid duplex ultrasound is the first-line investigation to assess for carotid stenosis in patients with TIA and carotid bruit.","Symptomatic carotid stenosis \u003E70% requires urgent vascular surgical review for consideration of carotid endarterectomy or stenting.","The combination of ipsilateral amaurosis fugax and contralateral motor symptoms strongly suggests carotid territory TIA."],"references":["Leung ES, Hamilton-Bruce MA, Koblar SA. Transient ischaemic attacks - assessment and management. Aust Fam Physician. 2010 Nov;39(11):820-4. PMID: 21301653. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2010/november/transient-ischaemic-attacks","Queensland Health, Royal Flying Doctor Service (Queensland Section) and Apunipima Cape York Health Council (2024) Chronic Conditions Manual: Prevention and Management of Chronic Conditions in Rural and Remote Australia 3rd edition 2024, Office of Rural and Remote Health, Clinical Excellence Queensland, Queensland Health.","Stroke Foundation. Australian and New Zealand Living Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management. Available at https://informme.org.au/en/Guidelines/Clinical-Guidelines-for-Stroke-Management. Accessed [02 July 2025]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22262"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-02T21:43:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T18:56:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15227"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107832"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}